post_text:
Pandemic Benefits Can Help You Buy Food

Hello Maud School families!

We are writing to let you know about an important resource to help families during the pandemic.
If your child was eating free or reduced-price lunch school lunch in March 2020, you are eligible for
food purchasing assistance of $250 per eligible child!

The Oklahoma Department of Human Services will be sending Pandemic Electronic Benefits Transfer
benefits, or P-EBT, to eligible families ‚Äì you do not need to apply. If you already have an EBT card the
benefits will be loaded on your existing card. If you do not currently have an EBT card, please look out
for a P-EBT card in the mail.

Watch closely as the outside envelope may not clearly say P-EBT.

P-EBT is provided to any child who was receiving free or reduced-price school lunch in March 2020.
It will not impact your citizenship or immigration status.

To learn more, visit www.hungerfreeok.org/pebt.
Thank you!

For our children:

Cindy White

Cindy White
Superintendent

post_text: ATTENTION PARENTS OF 6TH-12TH GRADE STUDENTS: We are accepting new students into the FOCUS Program through Seminole State College! Our program is a grant program from the US Dept of Education designed to help students prepare for and enroll in college or other post-secondary options. Our services are at your child's school and virtually (see link below for more info). We serve the following schools (whether your child will be online or in-person): Seminole, Varnum, Wewoka, Bowlegs, Butner, Justice, New Lima, Paden, Sasakwa, Strother, Shawnee, Tecumseh, Earlsboro, Maud, McLoud, and Macomb. As supplies last, we will be mailing this snack box and a STEM activity to applicants. If you are interested in signing your child up, feel free to message on here or through the office at a.harjo@sscok.edu or 405-382-9709, and we can either email or mail an application to you!

post_text: Summer Learning began this year on May 1 and runs through August 15, with a variety of ways to participate both virtually and from home. This year's Summer Learning Challenge - accessible here - rewards readers for time spent reading either a physical book or through the library's downloadable collection. But as with last year's Challenge, taking part in a variety of activities also will count toward a person's summer goal. There is a wide selection of virtual programs and activities on the PLS YouTube Channel which participants can log and count toward their goal. While individual libraries will not be able to present kickoff events at their locations, each library will be represented with a special Summer Learning Challenge Kickoff Week, scheduled from May 26 through May 31. Each day, two libraries will be represented with virtual kickoff programs offered through the PLS Facebook page. More information can be found on thePLS website‚Äôs home page.
